# ğŸ“˜ Week 5 Day 6 â€“ Palindrome Partitioning (LeetCode 131)

## ğŸ”¹ Problem Statement
Given a string `s`, partition it such that every substring of the partition is a **palindrome**.  
Return *all* possible palindrome partitioning of `s`.

This problem is a classic application of **recursion + backtracking**.

---

## ğŸ”¹ Approach

### âœ” Backtracking
1. Start from index 0 and try all possible substrings.  
2. For each substring, check if it is a **palindrome**.  
3. If yes â†’ include it â†’ recursively process the remaining string.  
4. When the string becomes empty, store the formed partition.  
5. Use backtracking to explore all possible valid partitions.

---

## ğŸ”¹ Time & Space Complexity
| Aspect | Complexity |
|--------|-----------|
| Time   | **O(n Â· 2â¿)** â€” due to generating all possible partitions |
| Space  | **O(n)** recursion stack + result storage |

---

## ğŸ”¹ My Learnings
- Improved understanding of **recursion tree exploration**  
- Learned how backtracking helps undo choices  
- Palindrome checking is crucial for
```cpp
  class Solution {
public:
bool ispallendrome(string s)
{
    string s2=s;
    reverse(s2.begin(),s2.end());
    return s==s2;
}
   void allPart(vector<vector<string>> &ans,vector<string> &partation,string s){
        if(s.size()==0){
            ans.push_back(partation);
            return;
        }
        for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++){
            string part=s.substr(0,i+1);
            if(ispallendrome(part)){
                partation.push_back(part);
                allPart(ans,partation,s.substr(i+1));
                partation.pop_back();
            }


        }
    }

    vector<vector<string>> partition(string s) {
        vector<vector<string>> ans;
        vector<string> partation;
        allPart(ans,partation,s);
        return ans;
    }
};
